45
00:01:42,937 --> 00:01:44,136
Good luck.

46
00:01:45,739 --> 00:01:47,239
Oh.

47
00:01:47,341 --> 00:01:50,275
As always, we'll be taking
the scenic route to history,

48
00:01:50,377 --> 00:01:53,745
Traversing switchbacks,
silver peaks and canyons,

49
00:01:53,848 --> 00:01:57,049
And a few overlooked historical
figures along the way,

50
00:01:57,151 --> 00:02:00,652
Figures that will help us
prove unequivocally

51
00:02:00,754 --> 00:02:03,956
How a mouse trap
can cure your hangover.

52
00:02:04,058 --> 00:02:06,425
Our story starts here somewhere
in the middle of maine,

53
00:02:06,527 --> 00:02:12,097
1854-ish with this kid,
hiram maxim.

54
00:02:12,199 --> 00:02:14,633
He's 14 years old,
and he works as an apprentice

55
00:02:14,735 --> 00:02:17,069
In this carriage
manufacturing facility.

56
00:02:17,171 --> 00:02:19,638
But at the moment,
hiram is not concerned

57
00:02:19,740 --> 00:02:22,341
With the manufacturing
of carriages.

58
00:02:22,443 --> 00:02:26,345
He is vexed by a far
more troubling problem --

59
00:02:26,447 --> 00:02:28,213
The presence of mice.

60
00:02:28,315 --> 00:02:30,582
Mice are everywhere.

61
00:02:30,684 --> 00:02:34,353
They scamper, they run,
they chew at his boots,

62
00:02:34,455 --> 00:02:37,055
Making him absolutely crazy.
Hiram's had enough.

63
00:02:37,158 --> 00:02:40,092
So he's spending his lunch hour
today on a mission,

64
00:02:40,194 --> 00:02:44,129
A mission to mass murder
all the mice in maine.

65
00:02:44,231 --> 00:02:48,800
In other words, the kid's trying
to build a better mousetrap.

66
00:02:48,903 --> 00:02:51,570
This curious kid
often went hunting,

67
00:02:51,672 --> 00:02:54,106
Bringing with him his trusty gun

68
00:02:54,208 --> 00:02:56,742
And the immutable laws
of physics.

69
00:02:56,844 --> 00:02:59,811
When the gun fires,
an explosion in the shell

70
00:02:59,914 --> 00:03:03,882
Propels the bullet forward with
a significant amount of force.

71
00:03:03,984 --> 00:03:06,785
But the force of the bullet
moving forward

72
00:03:06,887 --> 00:03:10,856
Is equal to the force
of the gun moving backwards.

73
00:03:10,958 --> 00:03:12,391
This lesson has been learned

74
00:03:12,493 --> 00:03:15,160
By anyone
who has ever fired a weapon.

75
00:03:17,198 --> 00:03:18,931
A painful lesson made possible

76
00:03:19,033 --> 00:03:21,867
By the one
and only sir isaac newton.

77
00:03:21,969 --> 00:03:24,836
I refer, of course,
to newton's laws of motion,

78
00:03:24,939 --> 00:03:27,406
Specifically the third law
that says every action

79
00:03:27,508 --> 00:03:30,008
Has an equal
and opposite reaction.

80
00:03:30,110 --> 00:03:32,377
That's the lesson
that young hiram learned

81
00:03:32,479 --> 00:03:33,946
When his gun knocked
him on his butt.

82
00:03:34,048 --> 00:03:37,349
Now he's applying
that lesson to the task at hand,

83
00:03:37,451 --> 00:03:39,885
Designing a better mousetrap.

84
00:03:39,987 --> 00:03:41,386
Here's the essential problem.

85
00:03:41,488 --> 00:03:44,590
The state-of-the-art mousetraps
of the day

86
00:03:44,692 --> 00:03:46,425
Worked pretty much
like this one.

87
00:03:46,527 --> 00:03:48,227
You'd set it and put some bait
on a hook

88
00:03:48,329 --> 00:03:50,095
And the mouse would come in
and take the bait

89
00:03:50,197 --> 00:03:51,330
And it would close,

90
00:03:51,432 --> 00:03:54,433
Thereby trapping a single mouse
inside this cage.

91
00:03:54,535 --> 00:03:56,368
Basically, you were one
and done.

92
00:03:56,470 --> 00:03:57,803
That's not what hiram wants.

93
00:03:57,905 --> 00:04:01,240
He wants to murder as many mice
as he possibly can,

94
00:04:01,342 --> 00:04:02,641
And he's going to do it

95
00:04:02,743 --> 00:04:04,876
With a little help

96
00:04:04,979 --> 00:04:07,012
From newton's third law.

97
00:04:07,114 --> 00:04:11,416
Just like a bullet, hiram's
mousetrap creates a recoil.

98
00:04:11,518 --> 00:04:14,253
The mouse,
lured in by the cheese,

99
00:04:14,355 --> 00:04:15,887
Falls onto the floor,

100
00:04:15,990 --> 00:04:20,025
Which triggers a reaction,
a recoil that closes the door,

101
00:04:20,127 --> 00:04:22,861
Resetting the trap
for its next victim.

102
00:04:22,963 --> 00:04:26,131
In other words,
a repeating mouse trap.

103
00:04:26,233 --> 00:04:28,267
Does he pull it off?
Yeah.

104
00:04:28,369 --> 00:04:30,302
Does he catch a lot of mice?
Yep.

105
00:04:30,404 --> 00:04:31,637
Does he patent it?

106
00:04:31,739 --> 00:04:34,139
Does he make a fortune
by mass-producing it?

107
00:04:34,241 --> 00:04:38,143
No. Hiram maxim leaves
a lot on the table

108
00:04:38,245 --> 00:04:41,213
In the early part of his career,
literally.

109
00:04:41,315 --> 00:04:44,316
If you look at
some of what he invented

110
00:04:44,418 --> 00:04:46,718
Over the years,
it's kind of mind-blowing.

111
00:04:46,787 --> 00:04:50,389
This is a lamp
for a locomotive.

112
00:04:50,491 --> 00:04:52,524
This is an early curling iron.

113
00:04:52,626 --> 00:04:55,594
This is reportedly
a better cup of coffee.

114
00:04:55,696 --> 00:04:57,429
Mm!

115
00:04:57,531 --> 00:04:58,930
Horrible miss on that one.

116
00:04:59,066 --> 00:05:01,500
This is a pipe of peace.

117
00:05:01,602 --> 00:05:03,402
It's basically an inhaler

118
00:05:03,504 --> 00:05:05,971
To help with the bronchitis
that he suffered from.

119
00:05:06,073 --> 00:05:10,108
This is a a gas engine,
one of the first of its kind.

120
00:05:10,210 --> 00:05:12,978
He also invented
the automatic sprinkling system.

121
00:05:13,080 --> 00:05:15,047
This is pure genius.

122
00:05:15,149 --> 00:05:18,784
This technology is in buildings
all around the world today.

123
00:05:18,886 --> 00:05:23,055
It puts the water
only where the fire is.

124
00:05:23,157 --> 00:05:25,691
Right. He patents it.
Does he make any money?

125
00:05:25,793 --> 00:05:27,125
No.
He lets the patent expire

126
00:05:27,227 --> 00:05:29,761
And then other people
come in and make a fortune.

127
00:05:29,863 --> 00:05:32,064
Here's another heartbreaker,
the light bulb.

128
00:05:32,166 --> 00:05:36,435
According to maxim, it was he
who invented this, not edison.

129
00:05:36,537 --> 00:05:39,104
He got ripped off in a patent
case that went to court.

130
00:05:39,206 --> 00:05:42,641
And long story short,
he was shafted.

131
00:05:42,743 --> 00:05:45,344
The story of the shafting starts
with a bottle of milk.

132
00:05:45,446 --> 00:05:47,813
At least william sawyer said
it was milk,

133
00:05:47,915 --> 00:05:50,615
But william sawyer may have been
filling his milk bottles

134
00:05:50,718 --> 00:05:51,950
With something else.

135
00:05:52,052 --> 00:05:54,786
According to his employer,
william sawyer was, quote,

136
00:05:54,888 --> 00:05:59,057
"an expert electrician,
but also a great drunkard.

137
00:05:59,159 --> 00:06:02,961
I made up my mind that
we had better get rid of him."

138
00:06:03,063 --> 00:06:06,665
Well, william sawyer's employer
was hiram maxim.

139
00:06:06,767 --> 00:06:09,201
Maxim fired sawyer,
but not before he made off

140
00:06:09,303 --> 00:06:10,669
With something valuable --

141
00:06:10,771 --> 00:06:15,340
The design for an electric lamp
which saw your patented in 1878.

142
00:06:15,442 --> 00:06:17,709
Enter thomas edison.

143
00:06:17,811 --> 00:06:20,912
If edison was good at inventing,
he was great at patent law.

144
00:06:20,981 --> 00:06:23,081
And edison argued
that sawyer's patent

145
00:06:23,183 --> 00:06:25,317
Wasn't novel enough to be valid

146
00:06:25,419 --> 00:06:28,820
And also was fraudulently
and illegally procured.

147
00:06:28,922 --> 00:06:32,991
After a protracted legal battle,
edison gets the patent revoked

148
00:06:33,093 --> 00:06:34,826
And edison knows
when that happens,

149
00:06:34,928 --> 00:06:36,628
The rights won't revert back

150
00:06:36,730 --> 00:06:39,364
To hiram maxim
or to maxim's company.

151
00:06:39,466 --> 00:06:42,667
Instead, they default
to another patent application

152
00:06:42,770 --> 00:06:44,836
Edison had filed.

153
00:06:44,938 --> 00:06:47,572
So edison becomes the accepted
inventor of the light bulb,

154
00:06:47,674 --> 00:06:50,342
Leaving hiram maxim s.O.L. --

155
00:06:50,444 --> 00:06:52,477
So out of lights.

156
00:06:52,579 --> 00:06:53,812
But he never gives up.

157
00:06:53,914 --> 00:06:56,448
He never stops tinkering.
He never stops drawing.

158
00:06:56,550 --> 00:06:58,850
A few years later,
he's back at it again.

159
00:06:58,952 --> 00:07:00,519
This is a helicopter,

160
00:07:00,621 --> 00:07:04,423
The first design,
except for maybe da vinci,

161
00:07:04,525 --> 00:07:06,691
But he's ready to
bring it to market.

162
00:07:06,794 --> 00:07:08,160
He's got it done.

163
00:07:08,262 --> 00:07:10,195
He just -- he just doesn't
put the ball through the hoop.

164
00:07:10,297 --> 00:07:13,465
He's full of good ideas,
but he's not really executing.

165
00:07:13,567 --> 00:07:15,300
And it really is enough
to make you wonder

166
00:07:15,402 --> 00:07:20,005
If hiram maxim is ever going to
do anything to make a killing.

167
00:07:20,107 --> 00:07:22,007
I'll give you a hint.

168
00:07:22,109 --> 00:07:23,742
He does.

169
00:07:26,547 --> 00:07:31,383
1881 -- it was an incredible
time for inventors,

170
00:07:31,485 --> 00:07:34,686
The phonograph, jeans,
the cash register,

171
00:07:34,755 --> 00:07:37,756
The light bulb, and more
had all just been released.

172
00:07:37,858 --> 00:07:41,259
All of these would have
significant impacts on society,

173
00:07:41,361 --> 00:07:44,729
But none inspired hiram
quite as much as the tidbit

174
00:07:44,832 --> 00:07:47,332
He received
while walking around.

175
00:07:47,434 --> 00:07:48,800
If you want to make
your fortune,

176
00:07:48,902 --> 00:07:50,469
Invent something to help
these europeans

177
00:07:50,571 --> 00:07:52,137
Kill each other
more quickly.

178
00:07:52,239 --> 00:07:55,040
In other words,
screw your passion project.

179
00:07:55,142 --> 00:07:57,843
The real money
is in weapons of death.

180
00:07:57,945 --> 00:08:02,581
